EXERCISE.

I admire his greatness of mind. We admire the greatness of mind [that characterizes] such men. The- mistocles addresses the king with much greater readiness and fluency than this man can, who was born in Persia. If you choose to follow my counsels, you will conquer Greece. Themistocles returned to Magnesia with great presents bestowed upon him by the king. I will present you with this city, to supply you with bread. The king promised to give Themistocles the city of Lampsacus, from which to supply himself with wine. There are [still] remaining in our days two monuments to Themis- tocles. C. Nepos says that Themistocles died at Mag- nesia of [some] disease : though he allows that his bones were privately buried in Attica by his friends. I despair of being able to make good what I have prom- ised the king with reference to the conquest of Greece. I fear that you will not be able to make good what you have promised the king. [Regin with rel. clause. See Pr. Intr. i. 30.]
